#Exit$Exit
    This selection ends the T3000 Operating System program and returns control to DOS. Upon selection of this command you will be asked to confirm if you wish to exit, type "Y" RETURN. If you do not wish to exit type "N" RETURN to remain in the system.  If you choose to exit, the system will ask you the enter the password that you logged in with. Once you exit from the system the T3000 application stops. Do not exit from the system if you wish to leave the building and have the building under control by the T3000.
@
#Logout$Logout
     Logout allows you to leave the operator station and keep the T3000 application running. This option prevents any unauthorized access to the system as access to the system is limited only to those who can properly Sign-On.
@
#File$File
    The "File" selection from the Panel menu operates on the T3000 panels complete programmed information.
@
#Select_panel$Select panel
    This option prompts the user to select a panel which becomes the "Selected Panel". All operations that are specific to that panel, such as entering the various types of points, creating monitors or writing control basic are done using the selected panel.
@
#Print_panel$Print panel
    Print produces a hardcopy of all the programmed information in the selected panel. It does this by first storing the print text in a file and then uses the DOS "PRINT" command to print the file.
@
#Clear_panel$Clear panel
    This selection does a complete initialization of a panel. All programmed information is cleared from the selected panel. Upon selection of this option the system will ask to confirm that you want to "Clear Panel". Type "Y" for yes; "N" for NO is the default.
@
#Load$Load
    The "Load" operation takes a file and sends it to a panel. This is the only operation that is required to restore a "blank" panel to normal operation. To select a program to load, make sure that the Drive and Directory information is correct. The system defaults to the information supplied in "File Paths". Then, either enter the program name at the blinking cursor, or hit RETURN and scroll to the appropriate program and hit RETURN again. When typing in the program name it is not necessary to include the .PRG extension. Upon selection of the program to "Load" the system will ask you to confirm that this is the program that you wish to load. Type "Y" for YES; "N" for NO is the default.
@
#Save$save
    The "Save" operation saves the information in a file. This saved copy then becomes the backup file if the T3000 should lose its program for some reason.
    To select a program to "Save", make sure that the Drive and Directory information is correct. The system defaults to the information supplied in "File Paths".Then, either enter the program name at the blinking cursor, or hit RETURN and scroll to the appropriate program and hit RETURN again. When typing in the program name it is not necessary to include the .PRG extension. Upon selection of the program to "Save" the system will ask you to confirm that this is the program that you wish to save. Type "Y" for YES ; "N" for NO is the default.
