#Screens$Screens
    Screens are used to group points of all types into one logical unit for displaying information on the screen. Thus the operator is able to see how a change in one parameter is affecting other related parameters. This enables the operator to see and change the value and auto/manual status of points. The operator can also call up the history information of a point or the program associated with that group. The elements of a screen can be displayed on top of a graphic picture to augment the display of information.
    A screen made up of other screens can be used as a menu. Screens may be nested indefinitely. The TAB key is used as a fast-exit key to the Main Menu. This is useful when many screens are nested and the operator does not want to escape through them  all. The "Page-Up" and "Page-Down" keys will take you through consecutive screens. A Screen can be programmed to load up automatically after signing on by entering the Default Screen number in the "User List" selection from Configuration. This screen then becomes that users Main Menu. 
    Screens setup fields: 

a)  Full_label
    A 20 character descriptor. 

b)  Label
    An 8 character label. 

C)  Pic file    
The name of a graphic file to be used as an underlay for the group's data. 

d)  Mode
    The type of Screen display either Text or Graphic. If a graphic display is choosen, the graphic will be overlaid onto the Screen if the following two conditions are met: 

1.The file is found in the drive and directory as specified in "File Paths" with the
extension ".TIF". 

2. The graphic file was drawn in the same format as the graphic capabilities of your
system. 

    To program or view an individual Screen press "Ins" while highlighting that group. The group is then loaded with its picture file (if it exists) and placed in modify mode. The work menu reappears if the cursor is moved to the top line of the display. If a graphic is loaded and you are using a mouse, the work menu appears when the mouse is moved to the top of the screen.
