#Inputs$Inputs
    The T3000 system controls a process by reacting to temperature, light, flow or other physical properties. In order to measure the physical property, a signal must be fed into the T3000 panel which is referred to as an "INPUT"  throughout this manual. Inputs may be either digital (ie. only two states, on or off) or analog (infinite states, 0 - 5.0 Volts). The standard T3000 can accommodate up to 128 Inputs with expansion
capabilities for a further 128 inputs. 
    Input setup fields: 
a)  Full_label
    A 20 character descriptor which is usually used to associate a give point with the physical location. 

b)  A/m
    When in auto the input is operational and will read the value from the sensor. When in manual the input is not operational and will remain at a fixed value. To change from auto to manual or vice versa simply highlight the field and press ENTER. 

c)  Value
    This field contains the value of the input point which may be digital or analog depending on the range selected. To toggle a digital value highlight the field and press ENTER. To change an analog value highlight the field and press ENTER followed by the new value and ENTER. Note that it is only practical to change an input value when the point is in manual. 

d)  Units
    The scale with which the Value is to be read. 

e)  Range
    The range field is set to match the sensor that is connected to the input. 
    To set the range highlight the field, press ENTER, and select either Analog, Digital or Custom Digital. Then enter the desired range number.

f)  Cal.(Calibration). 
    The value in this field is added into the measured value to adjust for sensor inaccuracy. The maximum correction is +/- 30. If the correction amount is between -3.0 and +3.0 there is 1 decimal point in the correction, otherwise there is no decimal point. 

g)  Filter 
    Filter is the number of samples that are averaged to give the value. A larger filter will slow the response of the system to a change at the input, but will filter out fluctuations that are not wanted. 

h)  D(Decommissioned) 
    This field is a flag indicating if the point has been taken out of service. The normal indicator is a dash (-), if decommissioned this field will have a Y (Yes) in it. If a point is decommissioned it will be flagged as such when displayed in control groups. 

i)  Label 
    An 8 character descriptor. 
