#Controllers$Controllers
    There are 64 Controllers in the basic T3000. These are 3 mode Controllers (Proportional, Integral, and Derivative - PID). See section 5.4.1 for the details of Controller operation.
    Controller setup fields: 

a)  Input 
    The measured variable being controlled. 

b)  Value 
     The value of the measured variable. 

c)  Units 

d)  A/m 
    When in "Auto" the controller is operational. When in "Manual" the controller is not running and the output will remain at the last value. 

e)  Output 
    The output value of the controller between 0 and 100%. 

f)  Setpoint 
    The point used as a setpoint. Setpoints are often set up as variables and changed within Burke Basic programs or they can be entered directly. 

g)  Set_value 
    The value of the setpoint. A number can also be entered directly here. CBAS can control this field if a setpoint is not entered in the Setpoint field. 

h)  Units 
    "Action". "+" is direct acting, "-" is reverse acting. 

i)  Action 

j)  Prop 
    The proportional band in units of the measured variable. 

    For example, suppose we have the following settings: 

    In this example, we are controlling a damper to maintain 10 Deg C supply air temperature as specified by "AHU4.SP" or the Air Handling Unit 4 Setpoint. The proportional band is set at 1, the controller will vary from 0 to 100% over a range of 1 Deg C. (neglecting the Reset and Rate terms which are set to zero for simplicity). 

    The proportional term can be thought of as the "rigidity" with which a valve or damper will react to being away from its setpoint. A large value will tend to make the valve or damper "Lazy", while a small term will cause the actuator to react quickly over a smaller temperature deviation. 

k)  Rset 
    The "Reset" in repeats per hour. The Reset action (also called Integral) works to correct for a steady state error between the input and setpoint. It "repeats" (adds in) the error to the  output of the controller at the "Reset" times per hour. 

     A controller with a large reset term will accumulate error faster and therefore cause the actuator to react quickly over time. A small term will cause the controller to accumulate error more slowly, therefore causing the acutator to react more slowly over time. 

l)  Rate 
    The derivative component in minutes. The Rate action (also called Derivative) works to
correct for a quickly changing error. It can only be used when the process is "fast" and no time lags are in the control loop (i.e. sensors, outputs devices, process). 

m)  Bias 
    Output bias in %. This is the value which the controller will reach at equilibrium if no reset is used. 

n)  Num 
