#Weekly_routines$Weekly routines
    Weekly Routines are essentially time clocks with 4 ON/OFF times per day of the week. The week has 9 days to allow for two overrides in addition to the weekly schedule. These are used for holiday schedules, and are specified by the Annual Routines Menu. 
    Weekly Routine setup fields: 
a)  Full_label 
    A 20 character descriptor. 

b)  A/m
    Controls whether the routine is operational or not. 

c)  Output 
    The state of the routine (ON/OFF). 

d)  Holiday1
     When point entered here is *On", the day will be the eighth day of the week. 

e)  State1 
    The state of Holiday1(ON/OFF). 

f)  Holiday2 
    When point entered here is "On", the day will be the ninth day of the week. Note that in the case of both Holidays being on, Holiday1 is regarded. 

g)  State2 
    The state of Holiday2(ON/OFF). 

h)  Label        An 8 character descriptor. 

    To program the times for an individual routine press the "Ins" key while highlighting the Weekly Routine to be set up. The 9 day week will be displayed with the standard work menu operations. The desired start and stop times are then simply entered in the appropriate fields. 
    Note that the times in Weekly Routines can be accessed from Control Basic using the WR-ON and WR-OFF functions. This is useful for programs that need to look ahead and see when an event is to start. 
    The times specified must be in increasing order throughout each day. 
    If no time is in a day column the Weekly Routine will maintain its current value. 
@
#Annual_routines$Annual routines
    Annual Routines mark holidays, or days for special action throughout the calender year.
    Annual Routine setup fields: 
a)  Full_label 
    A 20 character descriptor. 

b)  A/m 
    Controls whether the routine is operational or not. 

c)  Value 
    The state of the routine (ON/OFF). 

d)  Label 
    An 8 character descriptor. 

    To program the times for an individual routine press the "INS" key while highlighting that point. The year is then displayed in 4 calender format pages (use PgUp and PgDn keys to change page) with months available on each page. Work menu operations are again available. To set a day as a holiday move the cursor to the desired day and press "ENTER". 
    The Annual Routines defined here are the special event overrides which appeared in the previous section which described setting up the ON and OFF times for Weekly Routines (repeated below). 
    When the annual overrides are defined, they can be entered into the "AR1" and "AR2" fields of the Weekly Routine setup area shown above, in order to let the Annual Routines override the weekly routines. In the example above, we have entered "AR-1" or Mnnual Routine 1" to override the Weekly Routine defined by "AR-1" or Weekly Routine 1. 
@
#Arrays$Arrays
    Arrays are a table of variables that share a common name. The array elements can be accessed in Burke Basic by specifying the array name, followed by the index of the element. For example if there are twenty rooms for which we would like to perform some statistical calculations on, we could store the room temperatures in an array called ROOMTEMP. 
    To build the array, move the cursor to a clear area in the "Arrays" work screen and type in the name for the array(e.g. KWHMONTH or ROOMTEMP shown below). Give the array a dimension which will be the number of rooms you wish to store in the array  The array is now configured and can be viewed by pressing the insert key.  This will bring you to the array variable screen, as shown below. Arrays can be used in Control Basic and in groups. When specifying an index in Control Basic it is often useful to use an expression so that the variable selected is dynamic. Arrays are for use currently only in the T3000 panel. 
    Array setup fields: 
a)  Label 
    An 8 character descriptor for name the array. 

b)  Length 
    The number of variables in the array. Can be from 1 to 128. 
@
#Monitors$Monitors
    Monitors are used to collect historical data for any point defined in the system regardless of their nature (either Analog or Digital). A base T3000 system can handle up to 16 separate monitors. The number of monitors available is dependent on the amount of memory that your system has. With enough memory the system can easily handle up to 128 monitors. Each of these separate monitors can trend up to 14 points.
    Monitors setup fields:
a)  Label
    An 8 character descriptor.

b)  Interval
    The time between samples in hours : minutes : seconds.

c)  Length
    Time interval for which dates are maintained by the monitor. Expressed in the units of time defined by the “Units" field.

d)  Units
    The units of time the interval is being measured by.

e)  Size
    The size of the file needed to store the monitor's data.

f)  Status
    "ON" indicates the monitor is running, "OFF" indicates that it is stopped.

g)  Input 
    The name of the points to be included on the monitor. The TAB key is used to move the cursor to this section. The TAB or ESC key is used to return to the main monitor work screen. Up to 14 points can be monitored here per monitor. Of these 14 points only 5 may be digital, i.e. On/Off or Start/Stop. If more than 5 Digital points are entered onto the monitor than a warning flashes on the screen to indicate that you have entered too many Digital points. If this happens the Digital points over 5 will be deleted from the monitor.
    An Analog Monitor can also be commanded to sample from Control Basic by setting it to On or OFF ( i.e. amon1 = ON ). When this occurs the monitor samples all its inputs and restarts the interval time. In using this feature it is best to stop the monitor (s = 0), and control all the sampling from Control Basic.
    To access monitor data and view the graph, press the "INS" key while highlighting the desired monitor.
@
#Tables$Tables
    "Tables" are used to program up to 5 custom input ranges, or for use with the TBL function in Programs. To program an input range, enter the input voltage from 0 - 5 VDC in the left column, and the corresponding value in the right column. The units for each table are set in the Custom Units section of Configuration (see chapter 8  for more info). The tables do a straight line interpolation between points.Note: the numbers which appear in the "Value" column must be entered in ascending order and should cover the entire 0-5 volt range.
@
#Custom_units$Custom units
    This selection allows for eight unique digital units to be entered. These units show up in the Custom Digital list when entering ranges for Input, Outputs and Variables. All panels in a given network share the information given in the units table.
@
#Alarm_log$Alarm Log
    Alarms annunciate problem conditions in the system. They are generated by the ALARM and DALARM statements in Programs. The ALARM statement generates analog alarms and the DALARM statement generates an alarm only if the condition persists for more than a defined period of time. These statements allow for a custom alarm message which can contain a maximum of 69 characters. When an alarm occurs, the alarm message is sent to the printer along with the panel number from which the alarm originated, as well as the date and time. This message is also displayed on the alarm line at the bottom of the screen. This alarm line alternatively displays each alarm currently in the system. 
    The event of an alarm restoring (going out of alarm condition) or being acknowledged is printed with the time of their occurence. When an alarm is both acknowledged and restored it disappears from the system. The "Alarms" selection from the Main Menu show all the alarms currently in the system. It is from this selection that alarms are acknowledged.
    To acknowledge an alarm, select the "Acknowlege" operation and enter the desired alarm ID number shown along the leftmost edge of the display. Restoring an alarm is done in the same manner. The time at which an alarm occured can be seen by selecting the "Time" operation and highlighting that particular alarm. Alarms can be cleared from the system with the "Clear" operation by an operator with an access level of 5. 
    If there is any alarm in the system that is neither acknowledged or restored the beeper in the PC is activated. The beeping can be stopped by acknowledging the alarm or by pressing Ctrl A. The UNACK function in Programs can be used to trigger an event if there are any unacknowledged alarms. Alarms can be directed to specific panels with the ALARM-AT statement. The default is to alarm all panels. 
    For information on the programming of ALARM and DALARM statements see Chapter 10 on Control Basic Programming.

@
#Setup$Setup
    The Setup option deals with setting up the software end of the system. This information is saved in CONFIG.CNF and is loaded when B3000 is run.
@
#User_list$User List
    user List provides the means for system security and individual access to the system. Each user has to Sign-On with his name and give his password to gain access to the system.  There is space to allow for 32 different users and passwords.
    User List setup fields:
a)  Name 
    An eight character name of the user. First step for gaining system access when Signing-On.

b)  Access level
    The access  level the above user is working at.
    The system has 3 different access levels as follows:
    Level 0. Full Access    Full access to the system.
    Level 1. View Only      Not allowed to make any changes.
    Level 2/3/4..Custom    Access to different parts of the system is determined by system supervisor.

    To set the Custom Access, hit the *, * arrow keys on Access Level with the cursor pad. This will take you to the "Access Rights" screen. Here choose either "View", "Edit" or "NoAcc" for the 14 different parts of the system listed. This is what determines  the custom Access. Each of the 32 Users can have his own Custom Access. 

c)  Default panel

d)  Default screen
    The screen, the above user, first sees when signing on to the system. If the "Default screen" field is 0, then the default Work Menu is displayed after signing on. If the "Default screen" field is non-zero, that screen becomes the Main Menu for that particular operator. This can be either a text or graphic based display. 

e)  Password
    An eight character name of the user. Second step for gaining system access when Signing-On. If all is correct, then that user is logged on to the system according to the above parameters. 

    When entering your "Password" the characters entered are not echoed to the screen. The system first asks you to "Type new Password" and then to "Retype new Password". If both passwords are the same then you will be allowed to exit the User List. If however two different passwords are entered then the message "Password Unchanged " will appear. The password will then have entered and retyped again correctly before you will be granted access to leave the User List.
@
#Hardware$Hardware
    The Hardware option deals with setting up the hardware end of the system This information is saved in CONFIG.CNF and is loaded when B3000 is run.
@
#Default_program$Default program
    The Default Program is the program that the panel you are talking to is currently using. Once you have loaded a program into the panel, enter the name of that program here. To do this simply enter the name, there is no need to hit RETURN to enter edit mode in this option. ESC exits you from this option.
@
#File_paths$File Paths
    The file paths displayed are the file paths that DOS uses to access each type of file. This allows the operator to specify in which drive and directory each type of file resides (i.e.: C:\B3000\PRG\). This information is saved in CONFIG.CNF and is loaded when B3000 is run. The trailing backslash "\" is optional. 
    The operator has the option of putting all files into a "Common Directory" or to split the different types of files into "Separate Directory's". If "Common Directory" is selected then after entering the directory name, this file path will be displayed after each of the different types of files. Or each type of file can have a different file path listed after it. 
    To exit from this option hit ESC.
@
#Time_and_date$Time and Data
    The time and date is set through this selection. This is the only time in the entire system. It is sent to all panels and also sets the internal clock in the personal computer. 
    You are prompted to reset the time in hours: minutes: seconds - i.e. 14:32:34. 
    Next, you are first prompted to reset the date by month-day-year - i.e. 10-29-95. 
    To exit from this option hit ESC.
@
#Operation_mode$Operation Mode
    Operation Mode asks if you want to be in "Console Mode" or not. 
    You would choose "Console Mode" if you were working remotely from a PC either across a network or a modem and did not have any controller cards attached. By doing this you free up memory on your machine and increase communications speed, and also the user interface's speed as certain tasks that the B3000 system performs need not be run on your remote station. 
    You would not choose "Console Mode" if you work on a panel.
@
