#Screen_display$Screen
    A screen made up of other screens can be used as a menu. Screens may be nested indefinitely. The TAB key is used as a fast-exit key to the Main Menu. This is useful when many screens are nested and the operator does not want to escape through them  all. The "Page-Up" and "Page-Down" keys will take you through consecutive screens. A Screen can be programmed to load up automatically after signing on by entering the Default Screen number in the "User List" selection from Configuration. This screen then becomes that users Main Menu.
    The work menu reappears if the cursor is moved to the top line of the display. If a graphic is loaded and you are using a mouse, the work menu appears when the mouse is moved to the top of the screen. 

@
#Monitor_display$Monitor
    Graph Display work options: 
a)  eXit
    Exit the graph and return to the Monitor Work screen.

b)  Load.
    Loads a previously saved View from the list.

c)  Save 
    Saves the current view setup parameters to memory. If the screen is too cluttered, any of the points monitored can be disabled by clicking on the name of the item appearing at the bottom of the screen. The graph will then be redisplayed with the disabled point or points not shown. The disabled points can then be toggled back on by clicking on the blank space occupied by the name of the item before it was toggled off. A point that is disabled will appear in a gray box. A point that is displayed will appear in a colored box. A View entails displaying only certain points available on the monitor. For example, you may have 10 points on the monitor but wish only to see 4 of them displayed on the graph. This would be considered a View and can be saved for the next time you need to view it.

d)  Delete
    Removes a previously saved View from the list.

f)  Reset
    Resets the graph to display as many samples as possible based on the size of the graph and erases the new Time Base opened by operator. 

g)  Time Base
    The period of time displayed on a full screen. This time base can be altered to change the graphs perspective. For example the Time Base can be changed from hours to minutes.

h)  (Move Left)
    The graph can be shifted 1/2 screen left at the current zoom level by clicking on the "<-" symbol at the top of the screen, or use the corresponding keyboard key.

i)  (Move Righit)
    The graph can be shifted 1/2 screen right at the current zoom level by clicking on the  "->" symbol at the top of the screen, or use the corresponding keyboard key.

j)  (Zoom Out)
    While in the graphing mode, you can "zoom In" on the data to view the data from a closer perspective. The Zoom range must first be set below.

k)  (Zoom Out)
    "Zoom Out" resets the monitor back one zoom level. This can only be used after Zoom In has been used to restore the graph to its original display mode.

l)  (Zoom.)
    When you select "Zoom" you will be prompted for the two end points over which the new graph will span. Once this is done when you zoom in or out this is the span it will increase or decrease by.
@
